statement:
Answer the following multiple choice question. Check your answer very
carefully. Your answer will be marked right or wrong (work will not be
considered for this problem).

The value of the integral

\begin{align*}\int_0^{\infty} x^2 e^{-x} \,dx\end{align*} is

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
A. $e-1$
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
B. $2e-1$
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
C. $0.5e$
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
D. $1$
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
E. $2$
\end{description}

sols:
Using integration by parts, we get

\begin{align*}\int x^2 e^{-x} dx = -x^2 e^{-x} + \int 2x e^{-x} dx\end{align*}

And using integration by parts again on this integral we obtain

\begin{align*}\int 2xe^{-x} dx = -2x e^{-x} + 2 \int e^{-x} dx = -2x e^{-x} -2e^{-x} +C\end{align*}

we get

\begin{align*}\int x^2 e^{-x} dx = (-x^2 -2x-2)e^{-x} +C\end{align*}

Now that we have the antiderivative, we can compute the improper
integral

\begin{align*}\int_0^{\infty} x^2 e^{-x} dx = \lim_{b\to \infty}\Bigl(
(-x^2-2x-2)e^{-x} \bigr|_{0}^b \Bigr) = 2\end{align*}

And so the correct answer is E.
